    "en": "Paper 3: The Holographic Principle and Surface-Area Scaling in a Holosphere Lattice",
    "ja": null,
    "latex": null,
    "preview_source": "tier7-ingest-v0.2",
    "summary": "We present an operational, testable interpretation of holography in Holosphere Theory in which long-lived information is accounted for as a boundary defect ledger. The surface-area scaling of the defect inventory is taken as an upstream result (Paper A), with thermodynamic normalization delegated to Papers C and D. We model black holes as VROS-Bounded Coherence Shells (VBCS): coherence boundaries supported by the VROS scaffold (Paper J) rather than reflective material surfaces. In this transport-first framework, gravity does not require a persistent emission flux from the compact object; it arises from spatial contrast in admissible transport, summarized by a bounded coherence-potential gradient (Papers 19, 24, 62). We introduce and validate a residual-only near-horizon imaging diagnostic "
  },
